The Prague Stock Exchange fell to a negative at the end of the trade
After a sharp fall in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange corrected the losses.
Transactions in CEZ shares have reached almost half of the daily trade.
The Prague Stock Exchange has followed up on its fall on Monday since the beginning of Tuesday's trade, when it dropped by almost six percent.
This time, the stock drop on Wall Street is behind the decline.
The market's response to the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to support the stabilisation plan for the financial sector there, is also manifest in our country.
Share crash in Asia
The dramatic fall on Tuesday was experienced by stock exchanges in Asia, although indexes, but during the day part of the losses eventually deleted.
The Hang Seng stock exchange index in Hong Kong wrote off almost four percent during the trade, but later deleted part of the losses and reduced the drop to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors the movement of Chinese stock on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, dropped by 3.8 percent, in Shanghai the markets were closed.
Sydney's stock market was losing more than five percent, but in the end, the losses decreased to 4.3 percent.
According to Taiwan's index, the exchange dropped by 3.6 percent.
"The timing of the rescue action in the US is uncertain and will affect financial markets around the world," said the head of Hong Kong monetary office Joseph Yam.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines monetary policy itself, i.e. without dependence on China's central bank.
Hong Kong has interest rates at the same level as the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, American legislators should quickly return to negotiations and approve the proposal for support for the financial system.
Otherwise, other countries are threatened to feel the effects.
Bloodbath of American stock
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected a financial system support plan for which up to $700 billion was to be spent (almost CZK 12 trillion).
So the legislators ignored President George Bush's call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the underlying causes of the financial crisis and help stabilise the entire economy.
America's shares experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and the main stock indexes recorded the biggest fall in over 20 years.
Dow Jones' index dropped by almost seven percent and dropped to a similar extent last time in 1987.
The index fell before the vote, but once it turned out that the proposal failed in the House, the index found itself in free fall.
Congress has retreated: The US government can pump $700 billion into banks
US Congress leaders and President George W. Bush's government have agreed on a broader form of financial assistance agreement for the US financial system.
It will be voted on at the beginning of next week.
American legislators have made a breakthrough in talks about approving a bailout plan in the form of financial aid for the US financial system of $700 billion (approximately CZK 12 trillion).
But it is not yet won.
Congressmen must complete some details of the agreement before they can publish the final form of the law and vote on it.
The financial system support plan will be discussed on Monday at the House of Representatives.
On Sunday, Reuters told the chairman of the Committee on Banking and Financial Services of the House of Barney Frank.
In the Senate, according to sources, there could be a vote on the plan probably first on Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be approved should be the first important psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
But then there will be "sobering" due to the complexity of mechanisms to help markets achieve even in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have resolved our differing views on how the package should look like to stabilise the market," Democrat Nancy Pelosi said for Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could take place on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislators met with US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on Sunday night to give a definitive form to the government fund.
It should buy non-saleable mortgage assets from financial companies, which withdraw financial firms into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the whole system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement of a plan that will work and must also be effective on the market.
We still need to continue the recovery plan, but I think we're there," said Paulson.
Signal for Asian Trading
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on stock markets that are falling sharply.
According to Nevada's Democratic Senator Harry Reid, legislators are so keen to reach a definitive agreement in Congress on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors before trading on Asian financial markets, which are the first in the time zone where Congress' decision could affect Monday's trading.
However, it is not yet clear with certainty when both US Congress chambers will vote on the law, nor whether last-minute negotiations can be stuck on a problem.
The legislators hope to be approved in the next few days.
However, the law will still admit a number of changes.
The total amount intended to assist the system should be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is to be available as soon as possible, as President George Bush requested.
But Congress can block the release of the remaining amount if it feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, in a series of another $100 billion and later the final $350 billion.
Bush appreciated progress in negotiations
The President may veto this decision, but Congress may overrule his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was to obtain funding for buying bad mortgage securities, whose value fell because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgages, remained.
"We've worked everything out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the law on Sunday and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
America's President Bush is also satisfied with progress in negotiations.
His spokesperson, Tony Fratto, said that Bush is satisfied with Saturday's progress and appreciates "a mutual effort to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy."
Cutbacks on golden parachutes
President of the Senate's Banking Committee Christopher Dodd, head of the negotiator, said that the legislators agreed to be responsible for the money program, protection of taxpayers from losses, closure of reliefs, timing of financing the plan.
The new law is also intended to limit the so-called golden parachutes for the directors of the company participating in the programme and to set up a committee with supervision over the Fund.
That should be run by the Treasury.
"We have worked very hard on this, and we have made great progress towards an agreement that will work and be useful for the market and for all Americans," said Paulson.
The plan also provides for assistance for homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should negotiate new instalments for mortgages it buys in order to reduce monthly repayment costs for debtors and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological assistance
According to the chief economist Patrio Finance David Mark, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
"This is because it is not known what mechanism and at what price problem assets will be bought out.
