The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic already this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite advanced and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Yet there's something missing here - a virtual operator that would make the classic ones cheaper.
Maybe he won't miss long.
We have written on Mobil.cz many times about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
After all, the ČTÚ confirmed this, which pointed out that the SMS price is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, there may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high in comparison with Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to fight.
Maybe it sounds paradoxical, we have three mobile networks and penetrations high above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to beg to say that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, who has said in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic, is often accentuated by the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ).
It is probably true that the classic operator with his own network probably doesn't have much chance anymore (after all, it would probably be hard to find frequencies already).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant price reduction, to which classic operators also had to respond.
Even before the entrance of the pike such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, voices like ours sounded on the market in the UK.
But it turns out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
After all, we do not need to go too far for examples.
In February this year we informed you about the launch of the virtual mobile operator in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to obtain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
The financial group Penta is behind Mobilking, which owns, among other things, U:fona in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, they need much less customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators are usually profiled as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower offer of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheap as its competitors.
But, as the example of Mobileking in Poland shows, a bet on an unbiased target group can be quite a good move.
This operator specifically focuses on men.
"Right Men Choose Mobile Entertainment Company - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibertz CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is hard to say if a similar concept as in Poland could catch on with us.
Vodafone's spokesperson Miroslav Čepicický doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of service offer.'
In the Czech Republic, no chance, they say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobileking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very promising.
More likely the Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone interview for Mobile.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not in favour of this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything they can to ensure that no potential competitor arises.
The interest of launching a virtual mobile operator has long been unknown by the GTS Novera Group, which would like to take the next step towards becoming a real competitor of the O2 Telefonist in the field of corporate customers.
"We are very interested in offering our customers not only solid but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them in the negotiations," says the press spokesperson Pavel Kaidl.
Maybe it's a brighter time.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should be looking forward to perhaps by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At this time we do not think that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a fully-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any subject with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sršeň of the Press Department of Telefonika O2 said in his comments to Mobile.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, spokesperson for T-Mobila, adds in a rare agreement with O2: "We have not yet noticed any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build further."
He adds: "By the end of the year, a virtual operator can hardly appear in the T-Mobile network.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table to consider in this short term."
Vodafone tends to draw attention to meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepicický says: "We are open to dealing with potential virtual operators, especially in terms of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider most beneficial from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The process of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a fall in prices and thus to a decline in their profits.
Why, then, make it easier for such a competitor to enter?
The fact that operators can pull together when they are involved in something is also evidence of the pull around the origin of the U:fon.
Probably the greatest pressure towards the ČTÚ went at the time of the creation of U:fon from the company T-Mobile.
This is demonstrated by publicly available information from the ČTÚ website.
Now it is U:fon suitable as an argument why not allow a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented on this: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and, above all, on his services."
However, given this approach of mobile operators, it is directly striking that Czech regulatory authorities are not interested.
This is not just about the position of the Czech Television, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Great Britain and other developed countries - does not have the power to intervene in competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (ÚOHS).
But he took his typical stand on the whole issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after a contract was concluded between a mobile operator and a virtual operator to rent the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has yet been concluded, because the offer of potential candidates was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," Kristián Chalupa of the Department of External Relations said in reply to our question.
It may not surprise the operators' representatives to make such a statement.
It is more than considered from an office that is intended to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position on the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "In a foreign country, where virtual operators normally operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in prices for mobile telephone services. "
But apparently, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and price decline are not one of the interests of the UOHS.
In fact, the whole case is shocking when the three mobile operators are moved by their reactions.
The question, if it's really just a coincidence, is offered entirely by itself.
Just as the exact same price of petrol at petrol stations is certainly just a coincidence and a hard competition.
"The Office did not find any evidence of anticompetitive behaviour in this matter, and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore does not have a corresponding increased responsibility for their behaviour on the market.
The necessary tools for opening a mobile market for virtual operators are probably also missing from the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in his statement.
Interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many points at issue.
Of course, there is an analysis of relevant markets developed by the Czech Television, according to which telecommunications is the only market in terms of competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the network operator's approval is always needed to create a virtual operator.
And the mobile operator - it has quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So it has to be dominant in a particular segment.
However, even if we did not accept this argument, it should be at least a warning to the UOHS that three mobile operators are making a striking similar approach.
At the same time, complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
The responsibilities of the ČTÚ are then quite common in telecommunications, which the ÚOHS gives away from the whole matter.
We've met him in several cases like this.
Unfortunately, the extension of ČTÚ's powers to competition in telecommunications to the recently adopted amendment to the telecommunications law did not succeed, although many experts promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the UOHS must know more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It's possible when no one's watching
The operation of some pseudovirtual operators, which exist in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
They are companies that issue their own mobile phone service price lists, but they are only partially public.
These are usually multilevel marketing companies.
It offers its own mobile phone services such as Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The prices of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The magic is that the company acts towards the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a major customer then gets special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the trading conditions of all Czech mobile operators forbid a similar sale.
"If there were cases you are talking about, this could be a breach of the terms of the contract that we would be dealing with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová answered our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such activities will not be brought to the people responsible from mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three mentioned companies, it could be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are resisting such a procedure.
They have considerable profits from the activities of these companies and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepicický points out the possible problems: "The law of similar speculation allows, however, only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
Moreover, they must accept that the SIM card on their phone is not listed in their name, so they cannot have it fully with them as ordinary customers of mobile operators."
That should be the least weird thing about the CTU.
In addition, another question for the UOHS is being opened.
If mobile operators close their eyes to similar processes, why are they blocking the emergence of a virtual operator?
It must be added that the IOHS has quite strong powers to detect similar activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the operator's explanation that they have no idea of such activities and their business conditions forbid it.
♪ When we won't be the most expensive ♪
As has been said several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable drop in prices for services.
In fact, in virtually all countries where virtual operators were created, classical operators tried to defend them more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - too small or too saturated market, problems with the quality of services etc.
In developed countries, however, it was at these moments that regulatory authorities intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators but their customers.
Whether by formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created and another one was packed on it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities are throwing the whole case over like hot potatoes.
From our experience, we cannot shake the impression that confusion in competences is more than useful in these cases.
But let's not throw a gun in the bush.
If background information is correct and the virtual operator really shows up soon, the Czech mobile market may move again.
If one of the operators admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the refusal (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to four versions of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of Czech Statehood's Day presented new recordings of the national anthem where my home is.
The orchestra of the National Theatre, led by Jiří Bělohlávek, has newly recorded the Hymna.
There are four versions - with male or female solo singing, choir performance and instrumental wording.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka took up the singing.
The authors of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiah and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on iHNed.cz.
Bělohlávek considers Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymens.
He has already told Czech Radio that he has deliberately chosen singers with young representative voices that are distinctive and popular to sing solo variants.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that they had a clear diction in order to understand the text well so that they would be in harmony," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate the 175th anniversary next year.
Song Where my home was first heard in 1834 on the boards of the Estates Theatre in the original Czech play Fidlovackáček Josef Kajetán Tyl supplemented by music by František Škroup.
She gained popularity, and people spontaneously took her as their own.
The first verse of the song then became a natural part of the national anthem after the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
One of the seven national symbols remained after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
