Prague public transport on Wednesday for the first time can also ride to the chip
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will be recorded in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date on which the first passengers to enter the metro, tram and bus will take the first ticket instead of a paper ticket will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At this point, he can get about 100,000 people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day and 90-day and annual coupon (which will apply from 1 January 2009) and at the same time have their chip card uploaded to their info centres and workplaces of the Transport Undertaking in the Metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
Coupons can also be purchased from yesterday via the Internet on the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
Over 400 customers took advantage of the afternoon service.
Those who make use of the online store can definitely forget about the window in the subway stations, where they have so far had to stand regularly in long queues for paper tickets.
Coupon buys it online, and they record it on the Opencard card in one of the 13 branches of the City Library.
"A desk with a trained operator is available at these locations to help interested parties purchase online and also upload a purchased coupon on their card," said project spokesman Martin Přeběrý.
In addition to libraries it will be possible to record electronic coupons on Opencard also in self-service machines, which are installed in several subway vestibules.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, they resemble ticket markers, and passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyla, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Now there are five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," said Careful.
Coupon checks the driver's seat automaton
The vending machine service that starts working tomorrow is simple.
All you have to do is insert the Opencard chip card into it and the previously paid coupon will be uploaded to it itself.
Electronic coupons from tomorrow apply not only in the capital, but also in its surroundings.
Thus, on suburban trains and bus lines with the number 300 to 499, mainly the inhabitants of the Central Bohemia municipalities travel to the capital.
"On trains included in Prague Integrated Transport, the conductor is equipped with card readers to determine the time and bandwidth validity of coupons," said Filip Drápal from Ropid, which compiles timetables for Prague public transport.
Suburban buses have card readers built in the ticket office by the driver.
It is therefore necessary not only to show the driver the chip card on arrival, but additionally to attach the Opencard to the designated location on the side of the cash register.
This way the driver checks the validity of the recorded coupons.
"If a passenger needs to verify the validity of recorded coupons, there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drápal added.
Passengers who do not ride suburban buses and won't remember when their coupon expires can go again to self-service vending machines where coupons are recorded.
Here, information about the validity of their documents will be displayed on the display of the device.
The Sudetens wanted a referendum from the U.S.
In 1945, the Sudeten Germans requested the integration of Šumava with the United States.
It flows from a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemia Science Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to live at least under the patronage of the United States of America.
With such a wish, reportedly in 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans turned to the President of the United States.
This results, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and is now stored in the collections of the South Bohemia Scientific Library.
The Germans from Český Krumlov ask in a letter from the US President not to allow the return of "Sumava County" - taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich agreement - back to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly, and we really want to be sure that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," says the letter, signed "People who have the fate of Sumava at heart."
Since joining Czechoslovakia is supposedly giving the Sudeten Germans - in the knowledge of Czech national nature - hope only for brutality, ruthlessness, misunderstanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter from the US President ask that he take over Šumava the Protectorate for both present and eternal times.
