But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, once we start focusing on another species and open the questions of perception or general consciousness, we enter inconvenient terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat gets in danger, he will do the same thing as many other animals: pretend to be dead, flee or attack.
People behave in a similar way, from which some scientists conclude on comparable subjective experiences.
That's not what I believe.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to animal life.
This is because circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include side prefrontal cortex (because of its share in short-term memory and performance or control functions).
This vast area is much more developed in man than in other primates, and it seems to be completely lacking in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on prefrontal cortex, among them knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is different even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could conceal the language essence of a person: because so much of his perception is associated with a language, it is often said that consciousness depends on him.
In this case, we could rule out the animals.
But even if consciousness didn't matter, it would certainly be influenced by the language, so that the animal consciousness, however designed, would probably differ from most of our states of consciousness.
That's why it's hard to see what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it is impossible to measure either, because of the special hardware, to analyse it based on our own experience, we are faced with great problems.
Most of my leaders relate to the content of conscious experience, but in addition there is another aspect of consciousness that should be scientifically easier to access.
It would be possible to examine animal consciousness processes regardless of their content, and that is exactly what is happening in short-term memory studies in primates, especially in visualisation examples.
But this approach, taken by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses more on neural correlations of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: both may be identical, but maybe they are not.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the nefrontal cortex for the implementation of visualization.
What does that mean for feelings?
I derive them from the fact that an emotional system, such as a fear system, is activated in the brain conscious of its own activity.
So what we refer to as "fear " is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of a defensive system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as physical reactions) uses operational memory.
Seen from this angle, feelings are closely linked to those areas of cortex that are characterized by primates, and especially by humans.
In connection with language nature, there is a gentle moderation of perception, because by means of words and grammar we can distinguish and categorize states to attribute them to others.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the areas of the cortex and brain stem dedicated to physical feelings, like Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brain stem.
