Proudness and obstacles to the life of black people in a separate city
Hidden among the scattered amusement parks of the Greater Orlando, several miles from everything shiny, noisy and giant, lies a quiet city in which the pride and intensity of African-American life revives.
Eatonville, the first completely black city that was incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "a city of five lakes, three croquet fields, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, enough guavas, two schools and no prisons. "
Now it's a pilgrimage place.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville Zora Festival! to pay their respects to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains a party, even though she made it a tourist stop by including it in the Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers of the economic crisis.
It is still as independent, dignified and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural black people in Florida often resisted and shared their true feelings with a white man who "knows so little about us that he doesn't even know what he's missing. "
Even today, in the year when the black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, calls for an open debate on races, many of the locals remain cautious about the views of others.
"We pay great attention to how our story is told," says the 59 - year - old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It has to be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of the black rise and a community of nearly 2,400 people, where poverty rates are twice the national average.
It is a centre of literature, but it is also an oak shielded by the example of a southern rural black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes praised - that originated from American slavery.
It is not surprising that the inhabitants here are both proud and protective.
And worried about the idea of Eatonville really started with Zora, which is the only way the Hurstons say.
She introduced her hometown to the world through hearty books full of dialects such as "Mules and Men (Mules and Men) " (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God (Their eyes have watched God) " (1937).
Five paragraphs of Florida's tourist guide changed the city piece into road 17, which leads through the often passed center of Florida, in the stage of black history and human drama.
With the impact of a large drum in life and literature, Hurston introduced readers into the store of the first Eatonville mayor Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"On the left side of the road," she wrote, "is a white brown decorated modern national school with well-maintained courts and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, even though he can't read or write. "
She also mentioned the new husband of Dash's widow, and she wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits in an hourly hotel. "
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
This obviously wasn't a typical Fodor's publishing house.
It wasn't really a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"Zora said it the way it was," says 90 - year - old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls, who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she said.
Hurston is still remembered here as a vibrant eccentric who often returned after her family moved to Florida's Jacksonville.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin remembers that most of the time when she came to town, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that is proud of dignified clothing today.
Most of the population were fascinated, said Franklin, but many grinned.
"The people of Zora always liked to see," said Franklin.
But, he added, swinging on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "she never stayed too long. "
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were removed from the press.
Eatonville seemed to have forgotten her along with the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, the contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived before.
In Eatonville, there were no larger funeral ceremonies or large public readings.
"I don't think they understood her meaning for the world or her legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's biography, "Wrapped in Rainbows," published in 2003.
Change came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to stretch through the five-way highway instead of Kennedy Boulevard, which is a local two-way main road.
The spread of Orlando has already pushed interstate highway 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still getting out of a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, has ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950 ' s, the struggle to stir races brought hatred to the threshold of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white boys, they came and threw oranges and things at people who were sitting on the side," Franklin said.
"Actually, we had this lady who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car."
In a letter from The Orlando Sentinel of 1955, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's request for forced integration and stated that his decision in the Brown case against the Education Chamber was "a insulting rather than celebrating to my race. "
The residents now claim that the desegregation of schools, although positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the local youth.
"The Negro children were used to hugs - I remember - you hugged your teacher in the morning, hugged your teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathiri, Ella Dinkins' daughter, and CEO of the nonprofit group "Preserve the Eatonville Community."
This lasted until the teachers and pupils came from the same place, she added.
"You are not hugging your white teacher because your white teacher - I mean, there is a cultural barrier," said Ms. Nathiri.
However, civil rights have helped create room for many other Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors and artists who, like her, have risen above prejudices with reckless self-esteem and quotes such as "How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand."
In 1975, Alice Walker arrived at Hurston's unmarked grave and began to fight to revive her reputation.
Five years later, Robert E. Hemenway's biography of Hurston, who re-built it in the American canon, came to the shelves in bookstores.
The project with the freeway arrived just as Eatonville's most famous daughter re-founded the ramp lights.
Hurston's former neighbors now considered her a savior.
To show what could happen to its highway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived at the inaugural event two years later, and every January many return to the celebration.
After a few years, the state withdrew from the highway proposal.
"The five currents of the highway have resurrected, you would say that it has blown up the real civil pride," Nathaniri said.
Boyd said it easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
Victory over the highway project helped change the image of the city.
Outsiders like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began to attend the church here in 1993, began to appear in a larger number, and residents began to rethink the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historical Register in 1998.
The new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) was opened in 2006 on a re-tanned and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: only six miles from the centre of Orlando can sometimes act as a backwater alley in the summer rain, as small as when it was founded with only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today it's 90 percent black.)
Strangers who come to find the story and meaning of Eatonville are still often treated with caution.
It is necessary to have permission for most interviews in advance and certain things - like wall paintings in the oldest Eatonville church painted by white people and depicted by black people in the fields - must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a courageous, confident teacher who likes deep red, still fear that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And even as the Hurston festival got bigger, domestic pride also increased.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw her whole race: beautiful, with problems and so on, but not better, not worse, and as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
From the voice of Franklin's nephew, 18 - year - old Edwin Harvey, a heartfelt love for the village sounds when he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in a local government or a police force that he says would use some help.
And even younger, like the 11-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they just pass through here, think, 'Oh, this town is nothing against the others,' said Alondra Kenon recently after church on Sunday.
"But if you really stop and look into history for a while, it's a very nice city."
