The Ministry of the Interior requires that a driver with three administrative sanctions for driving under the influence of alcohol must install a system in his vehicle to prevent him from starting his car in drunkenness or if he does not breathe.
The proposal became known already in June of this year and is now included in the Annual Report of the Supreme Prosecutor, according to which it is a pilot project that will last one year.
Its aim is to return the driver to the wheel, which is why drivers will also have to take a course of traffic reeducation.
In addition to the National Transport Safety Authority, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Institute of Technology for Car Safety (FITSA) will participate in this experience.
According to statistics between 30 and 75% of the car drivers charged more than once for drunk driving, he will be back behind the wheel.
Alcolock should prevent this from happening as it is a system connected to a vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not breathe before or if it is recorded above the permitted alcohol concentration.
Its price exceeds EUR 1,000 and would have to be paid by the culprit himself.
A study conducted in this sense in the USA in 2007 showed that, for vehicles equipped with this equipment, in the course of the first year after the introduction, offences decreased by 65%.
In Spain, 115 people are expected to be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with this behaviour before it results in a criminal offence.
And in order to help introduce it, because the legislation can be implemented in the usual way, the necessary regulation of criminal provisions requires a change of law.
The equipment is not yet available on the Spanish market in any sales version, although some industrial cars and public service vehicles have already been installed in the testing room.
It is tomorrow that Congress of Members will vote on the proposal of the PSOE (Spanish Workers' Socialist Party) in which it is recommended to install this system on school buses, as is the case in France.
