Sleeping Talking
Some kids talk at night.
I don't mean the ones who wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but the kids who talk while they sleep.
When it happens for the first time, it may startle you, but it's actually meaningless.
This is a harmless sleep disorder called somniloquie.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure some of you were told that he spoke in his sleep last night.
This phenomenon may occur very sporadically (e.g. once in a lifetime with high fevers), or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once every few months...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There isn't only one reason to explain her arrival.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders such as nightmares, nightmares, ecuresis nocturna (night wetting) or sleepwalking, but it does not have to be.
As mentioned earlier, it can often accompany very high fevers, stressful or heated situations.
In any case, it is a little researched phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also different.
A child can speak in a calm voice, say single words, whisper, or just the opposite (screams, weeping, long speeches...).
In cases where a child manifests himself with great power, it would be advisable to observe and consult an expert to see if he has a problem that causes him great anxiety and thus manifests himself.
We said it was a harmless disorder, so it is not treated only if it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example if it is associated with apnea syndrome or with permanent stress).
However, we can do that by bearing in mind a few very simple preventive measures, such as:
Trying not to upset the baby too much before she goes to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent TV programs or series.
For very nervous children and those with work to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them gain some inner peace.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
When somniloquie appears, try to remain calm.
Remind yourself that she is harmless to the child and that she will no longer remember what happened the next day.
Useful Advice
Don't wake him.
It's pointless because he's not conscious and you're gonna stop him from sleeping.
Even when he talks, he sleeps, and therefore rests.
Remember that if you feel that he is very troubled several times in a row, it would be advisable to turn to counsel or to find out what causes such anxiety in a child.
If it is understood what he says (which is not so common), avoid the temptation to interrogate him and draw information from him.
It won't do any good, because when he's asleep, he's not conscious so he can get his thoughts together.
Moreover, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming of, and therefore why he is saying it, so be very careful how you interpret information and what conclusions you draw.
Never tell a kid you can ask him about his secret at night.
Not even for fun.
This causes great anxiety.
Don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's just an episode that takes only a few minutes.
