In order to face the demonstration of the forces of fishermen who, on Monday, severely disrupted the accessibility of several Breton and Norman ports, the French President decided to go to Guilvinec port in Finistère on Tuesday morning to meet their representatives there.
The latter promised to be adopted "in a constructive spirit, " hoping to" come up with concrete proposals. "
The presidential visit comes at the same time as the General Assembly of the "crisis committee" created by the Breton fishermen in order to take action against the sharp increase in oil prices, which reached a peak above 1,14 euros per litre on average.
According to Elysian Palace spokesperson David Martinon, the president will "speak to them about solutions that can be imagined in trying to help their companies regain competitiveness and better secure the conditions of employment and payment of sailors"
Nicolas Sarkozy is expected by fishermen with firmness.
On Tuesday morning, they performed a snail operation in Morbihan and Calvados departments, causing nearly 10km of traffic.
The holiday port in Quiberon was also blocked, but the connections in the direction to Belle-île were not interrupted.
A filter dam was put into operation on the Quiberon Peninsula.
Sailors proved their determination on Monday, when the demonstrations took place in Concarneau and Saint-Brieuc in front of the fuel depots of the ports of Brest and Lorient.
The movement spread to other ports on the Atlantic coast and the Channel of La Manche, as to Sables d'Olonne in Vendée, where the trawlers remained in the port, or to Le Havre, where about twenty vessels blocked the operation of merchant ships.
The fishermen from Turballa and Croisic in the Loire-Atlantique area stopped the blockade of the important total refinery in Donges during the evening.
Those of Boulogne-sur-Mer decided to wait until they eventually decided to act themselves until Wednesday's meeting at the Ministry.
In Guilvinec, the "crisis committee" is scheduled to decide on Tuesday how to continue the journey and its participation in the upcoming meeting at the Ministry of Agriculture and Fisheries in Paris.
However, some Breton fishermen do not want to be represented by the leaders of the State Department of Fisheries who did not support their movement.
"The strike will continue" because "the fishermen will not drop anything" and "they do not want to come to Paris" said, for example, Liliane Cariou, chairman of the Lorient Fisheries Department.
Professional fishermen who do not pay oil tax are currently paying about 50 cents per litre, but they consider that the return threshold for the ship is only reached when the oil is below EUR 0,30 per litre.
