Young people and opponents of the regime demonstrated on Sunday night at the main square of the Belarusian capital to reject the results of the parliamentary elections in advance.
Several hundred Belarusians gathered on Sunday night after the closure of the polling rooms in the main square in Minsk to protest the irregularities of the elections to Parliament.
Although no results have yet been announced, many young people have come to demonstrate against President Lukashenko's regime: "Dictator, resignation."
Some admit that they did not even go to the elections: "What would be the point of doing whatever they want with my voice anyway, " says a young man.
They do not believe that this regime, which has been friendly to foreign observers in order to renegotiate negotiations with the European Union, would be ready to make a turn towards democracy.
Penalties, such as the ban on visas for 40 Belorussian chiefs and the freezing of certain assets, could be abolished if the elections were considered clean by the observers.
According to the opposition, this was not the case.
"We were kept away from the electoral committees and our observers were not allowed to participate in the census," complained Yuri Potemkin, spokesperson for the Union of Democratic Forces, a diverse group of twelve parties.
"It is a cosmetic change," emphasizes Alexander Milinkievich, a former opposition candidate in the 2006 presidential election and a leading figure in the pro-European movement, "the important thing is who is counting the votes, and in our country it is executive power.
If any opposition Members make it to Parliament, it will be by being appointed and not elected.
However, their entry into parliament may mean television, regional meetings and bills."
The opposition therefore feels obliged to participate in the political functioning, because "a dialogue with the European Union needs to be initiated.
If our economy, deeply indebted to Russia, is affected by crises and we do not reform, we are in danger of becoming a protectorate of Russia.
But we want to be independent."
The opposition fears that the Organisation for Security and Cooperation in Europe, which has followed the course of the elections, should not declare the elections valid.
It stresses that participation seems too high and that the general introduction of an early vote (26% of the electorate in Minsk) has opened the way for all possible manipulations.
"Have you noticed that there have been any elections?" asks the Social Democratic leader Alexander Kozulin, one of the last two political prisoners released in August of this year.
"There wasn't a foot in the polls.
