The night silence once again took place in the October square.
On TV, President Lukashenko and members of the Central Election Commission congratulate themselves on their success.
Interview - Blood That Is Sure Again
Hema-Québec celebrated the tenth anniversary of the founding yesterday and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Hema-Québec became one of the most reliable and efficient suppliers of blood in the world.
First of all, he regained public confidence, which was seriously shaken after a blood-contaminated scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is generally known, the state blood reserve administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Department was contaminated with the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and the wave of indolence to the public, the Canadian Government launched a public investigation in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, which aimed to explain the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to formulate recommendations that such a disaster should not be repeated.
While Judge Krever was delaying his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélinea Committee held this role.
After Gélineau and Krever's report, two suppliers were set up in Canada: Hema-Québec, who was to manage Quebec, and the Canadian blood company to supply all provinces and both territories.
"When Hema-Québec started his activities in 1998, barely 38% of people had any confidence in the Quebec blood system," Dr. Décary recalls.
"The situation was depressing.
We have regained the public's confidence over the next few years with constant efforts to increase the safety of blood products and permanent work in this area," he says and proudly adds that at the beginning of 2008 Hema-Québek was already almost 94% of the population of Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of "confidence is something very fragile. "
Since its founding September 28, 1998 Hema-Québec has applied the principle of caution.
"Then we witnessed many cases of human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of a disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease," says the woman who has been leading the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could spread with blood.
We therefore relied on one of Krever's and Gélineau's basic recommendations, according to which if we do not know this and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, must be taken excruciating measures.
Thus, in April 1999, we rejected blood from people who had stayed in the United Kingdom since 1980 for more than one month.
A few years ago, it was safely proved that the disease was transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that sticking to the principle of caution was meaningful."
In 1999, a much more accurate technique appeared on the market to detect HIV: nucleic acid (NAT) tests that allow the donor blood to detect the presence of the virus itself and not the presence of antibodies on which the tests previously used were based.
The NAT tests have allowed the deaf period between the moment of the patient's infection and the moment when the first viruses can be detected by our blood techniques, explains the specialist.
We've been able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing and without finding out.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
The risk of getting blood contaminated with HIV is now exposed to one person in 12 million.
" In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone gets HIV.
Since Hema-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products each year, it will take 24 years for the first case of transmission of HIV through a blood product to appear.
I believe that today we can get or prescribe a blood transfusion necessary to heal," says Hema-Québek's head of management.
"The challenge for the next decade is to preserve the safety of our products.
We never know what kind of disease element might appear in the system.
Just last year, a chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by insect bites.
We must always be cautious," continues Dr. Décary, stressing that, in addition to safe supply, Hema-Québec must also count on sufficient supplies.
"The needs are growing because the population is getting older.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
Population ageing also has consequences for a network of blood donors, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecs allowed for donation."
Each healthy person aged at least 18 years, corresponding to the criteria of admissibility, but can only donate blood once every 56 days, which means six times a year.
On average 14% of people offering blood are not accepted because they are, for example, AIDS or malaria carriers, and if they have visited a land where mud fever is rampant, they are excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3% we can maintain a condition that meets the needs of hospitals.
Weaknesses are very rare.
However, members of the donor network need to be supplemented in proportion to how old they are and no longer able to donate blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to give blood, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so loose today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $ 297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before they are deposited with Hema-Québek, who also manages the only public blood bank from the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, previously considered biomedical waste, has blood-rich stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousand blood samples from the umbilical cord into the bank, and we assume that we will be taking over a thousand of them a year.
At the beginning of next year we should start offering them for transplantation," says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Hema-Québec does not have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
