Opinions - Orwellovsky discourses of Barrick Gold
In September 17, Le Devoir published a letter from Patrick J. Garver, the executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, it confirms that the world's largest gold producer has begun prosecuting three authors and a poor little publishing house for insulting honor in order to provoke a "transparable public debate" and demands six million of them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially in the event of prosecution for insult to honor, but the law.
It's no surprise that Garver is completely passing away from this crucial distinction.
Or is it the best way for Barrick Gold to have a public debate to bankrupt anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome, the authors and publishers of the book Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable sums in order to be prepared to defend themselves and fight a very unbalanced fight against the army of lawyers supported by almost bottomless pockets of the mining company.
Indeed, tactics in these unbalanced struggles often lie in ruining the defendants in order to enforce a conciliation procedure that will clog the mouth of the counterparty and, moreover, frighten anyone who dares to pursue this matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she had her eye on the whole thing to present public opinion.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, Canada normally has a debate in the exchange of ideas, rather than in the blows with a baton.
Thus, mining companies were not enough to open their books, their documentation, and establish a real debate through newspapers, media, publications, and the funding of independent scientific teams that could bring light into the matter.
However, Barrick Gold does not seem to have confidence in public opinion, and smahem rejects petitions and letters to support the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he could demand a "public debate" and at the same time despise the views of the same public?
It seems that this word in the vice president's world refers only to fat-paid lawyers and not all Canadians; that is a rather narrow concept of this term.
In democracy, even the Nazis have the right to speak.
Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public that supports authors and publishers of Noir Canada does so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of mining companies.
The public is prepared to hear and judge the matter, but on the basis of a civilised exchange of arguments, not in the context of what many see as prosecution, in which the defendant's mouth is to be blocked (in the context of his prosecution of the "public debate" by the way, Barrick has just called on Noir Canada's authors to officially announce that they are to stop using this term...).
Aside from Garver's surreal speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on university freedom of research and the search for truth that is essential to every democratic society.
Overall, it denies the right to quote credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations which form the basis of intellectual activity itself.
If, in a country like Canada, it is impossible to study and discuss topics that do not please rich companies in this world without exposing ourselves to repeated prosecutions, who else will be able to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, she could have created it if it had followed the scientific standards that Noir Canada's authors use.
He has the right to an answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's exaggerated action clearly shows that, despite what he claims, he does not have the slightest desire to hold a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to introduce measures that would restrict such a type of wrongful prosecution.
