The Bush administration and Congress leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the greatest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to slow down the financial crisis that has been on Wall Street for months with $700 billion has yet to be approved by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it envisages: better control of elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms ensuring repayment of public money deposited, new measures to capture the quantities of buildings seized due to non-payment, as well as the right to monitor the level of wages paid to the managers of the rescued companies.
US Finance Minister Henry Paulson, President of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced this good news yesterday a few minutes after midnight, after the end of the two-day negotiating marathon.
"We have made great progress and we have reached an agreement that will be effective on the markets," said the Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done so that the real economy and ordinary Americans are safe from the crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"This is a crucial point: if we do not do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption of everyday life of Americans will be huge," said Republican Judd Gregg.
During the last few hours, negotiations have taken place to the utmost turn for fear of the effect of further failure on investors' state of mind.
The designated time limit was the opening of markets this morning.
Both candidates for the US President were invited to negotiate later and both expressed their views on the agreement, but without neglecting to express their discontent that it was necessary to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has credited himself with adding an agreement on certain measures, in particular those aimed at enabling owners to maintain their residence and the wage arrangements for the leading state of employment of the rescued companies.
"When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibleness of some people, there is nothing to congratulate themselves on.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on TV waves.
His Republican opponent John McCain, who was asked by another station to vote in favour of the proposed plan, replied: "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The rough features I have read show that it is something that we will all have to spend and how it will be possible to move forward.
Inaction is simply unacceptable," he said.
The 700-billion-dollar plan aims to buy off dubious claims and risk-free and unselling assets of US financial institutions for taxpayers' money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes), then transferred to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in the freezing of cash and the breakdown of banks and financial institutions.
The decline in the first draft agreement last week was caused by Republican Members.
From the moment the Democrats agreed that some "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty would only be guaranteed by the government, but would not buy them out, there is a belief that the impossible situation is over.
In an effort to bring conflicting views closer to Congress, a measure has been added that the government will be able to introduce new charges to help it recover its deposit if, as a result of the programme, it has to take up losses for five years.
The new plan envisages a deposit of the first amount of 250 billion, to which an additional 100 billion can be added if the President considers it necessary.
The deposit of another 350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will acquire shares in rescued companies that will pay him dividends in the event of profit and which he will be able to sell again when this is over.
The Federal Government will be able to delay the real estate seizure procedures associated with the loans covered by the plan, as well as to set limits on the amount of valuation and compensation paid to the managers of the affected companies.
The authors of the plan would like to put him to the vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet certain whether their plan will have a green light.
Yesterday, voices continued to rise against this project in both Republican and democratic camps.
"It is quite clear that Washington cannot hear you," said Republican Scott Garrett, Member of the House's Financial Commission, at the address of the voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But earning money from taxpayers is not the solution."
Democratic representative Brad Sherman, presenter of a group of congressmen nicknamed "the skeptical committee," presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"The four hundred esteemed professors of economics, among them three Nobel laureates, wrote to us: we ask Congress not to rush too much and carefully examine which way to go," he said yesterday.
At the same time, Europe was once again confirmed that this crisis was a global crisis.
At the end of the emergency meeting, three Benelux countries announced a partial nationalisation of the Fortis banking group for EUR 11,2 billion (USD 16,3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French Bank of BNP Paribas announced that it had withdrawn from buying its competitor, which has been on the verge of collapse since it lost EUR 2 billion ($2,9 billion) as a result of the US housing credit crisis.
Fortis employs 85 000 people, one of the 20 largest European banks and one of the ten largest insurance companies.
"We will not lose this money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
"In return, we acquire the right to vote in the bank and influence.
And that is what savers and households can appreciate today's uncertain times."
On the other side of the La Manche channel, it seems that the British government has launched the nationalisation of another bank affected by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing loans from Bradford and Bringley, of which more than USD 41 billion ($75,5 billion) were loans to buy real estate.
According to yesterday's announcement, branches and accounts of British bank clients will be purchased by Spanish bank Santander.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock, which the British government has to nationalize since the beginning of the financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of socially engaged icon
His beauty with azure eyes long represented his trump, according to other weaknesses.
Did this American actor break out with a charming smile of narcissism?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensitivity, and unstoppable talent he possessed also distanced him from the force category that produced real stars.
But what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died on Friday at 83 at his ranch in Connecticut due to lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the fat years of American cinematography.
Less magnificent than Brando, to whom he was similar and for a long time was a rival on a film screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the disintegration of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often breeds beautiful children.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and mother originally Hungarian.
From these European roots was born one of the famous faces of the American dream.
Without excessive ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because this whole country was in love with a self made man, a warrior in the war in the Pacific, wounded in a battle that in the early 1950s studied acting at Yale, then visited New York's Actor's Studio and celebrated triumph in the theatre, on television and early in the film.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also a car racer who placed second at a 24-hour race in Le Mans in 1979, and also a sexual symbol, despite the fact that since 1958 he has been a model couple with actress Joanne Woodward.
It also leaves the dark spots of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the fuss of its own show-business, which will forever remain to some extent mysterious.
A decent man, in the most noble sense.
Paul Newman's departure this weekend caused the film lovers dizzy, while his big roles compete on the black canvas of memories.
More than half a century later, he's been defiling the ever-changing American seventh art.
The charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969) reappears in memory, a young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in Cat on a hot roof, adaptation of Tennessee Williams from 1958.
From the less ancient past (1990), we recall his sensitive Mr Bridge, troubled at an advanced age by marriage, which did not meet all expectations.
