According to the prosecution, they used money obtained in competitions for their own purposes and often supported tasks with fictional invoices.
The money from the state and government - in total about 65 million forints - went partly to the Fiatal Baloldal cash register, partly into the pockets of individuals.
The way in which the investigating authority also informed the investigating authority was that the money received in the competitions was collected on the basis of invoices for which there was no actual consideration and the commitments made by the association were never met.
According to the prosecution, a large proportion of the invoices were fake.
The forms for these invoices came from the Yózsefváros market and round stamps were produced in Kiskunhalas.
