Trumping Psychology: Why are we spending more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this famous - and seemingly irrational - behavior have been revealed to researchers in the field of neurology and economics of New York University.
According to their study, published in Science, people don't want to fall behind in eBay auction-type competitions, so they'd rather pay too high a price.
Research was using an experimental auction to map the pattern of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers planted, the other group participated in a staged auction, using a functional magnetic resonance method (fMRI) to examine the active areas of the brain of test subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction game, the important element of which is to trump the other side, the whole under the cerebral cortex called stratum began to work intensively when losing.
In addition to many other functions, this brain area plays a role in the "self-reward" mechanism of the nervous system.
According to researchers, it is therefore possible to explain the effort to avoid a severe reaction of the striata.
To support their theory, members of the economists research team conducted a financial cross-cutting investigation.
On various conditions, three groups were criticized against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was and they made the bets.
Moreover, members of another group were promised that if they came out victorious, they would still receive $15 for a reward.
On the contrary, the third group received $15 before the auction, but in the event of the loss, its members lost the money.
So the difference between the two groups was all about winning and losing.
Of course, members of the group playing "against loss" were willing to go higher than it was in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
"These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
Those have so far explained the phenomena observed in auctions by the joy of winning and avoiding risk.
Up to neurological imaging methods helped us resolve the contradiction between these two theories by now reaching a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of New York University Economics.
Hepatitis: when to seek medical advice?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infections, and this chronic liver disease is reported among the main causes of death in Hungary.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated to be 100,000, but only 7,000 of them are treated, and the reason for this is that the sick often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a summary of infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, the inflammation of the liver and jaundice is characteristic, but the agents of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
The hepatitis viruses, depending on the agents of the disease, are spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e. g. infected foods, water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretions, saliva).
In any case, travelers should be protected by vaccination against virus A and B, there is no vaccine against virus type C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A occur two to three weeks after ingestion of an infected meal, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal discomfort, nausea.
Then the skin and eye whites develop jaundice, lighten stool and darken urine. The treatment may take two to three weeks.
Every year, a million people around the world die of a more serious type of disease, liver cancer, and hepatitis B-induced cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason is that according to estimates, only 1 in 10 infected patients are treated with medication.
hepatitis C may also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it may lead to cirrhosis of the liver or liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know the cause of the disease destroys the liver cells insidiously, so the first symptoms occur in many cases up to 20-30 years later.
Therefore, early prevention, regular writing is very important.
In three groups, the disease occurs much more frequently than on average: among people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users and between people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated worldwide number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can already demonstrate a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his physician if he records any signs of unknown origin.
In early detection, the disease is treatable, the virus can be removed from the organism, preventing contagion and preventing cancer.
September 30 is the world day of hepatitis, which was organized for the first time worldwide by organisations representing the sick in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early recognition of the disease.
Who believes in God, doesn't it hurt so much?
According to recent research, faith in God acts as a kind of analgesic that could make death easier for Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment, examining how a person's belief in a god of perception of pain was influenced, reported the British daily Telegraph.
In a rather bizarre survey, they subjected 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists to electric shocks, while all watched the painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to rule out much of the pain.
Thanks to a technique that examines the human brain in detail, it has also been shown that Catholics have been able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for regulating pain.
Research is the first of a series of researches involving scientists, philosophers and theologians from various parts of the university.
Exactly the test was carried out by attaching a sparking instrument to the test subject's left hand, which gave rise to electrical shocks.
The researchers asked the participants to watch two paintings: the Sassoferrat Virgin Mary from the 17th century and the Lady with the Edge of Leonardo da Vinci, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the research hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary would bring about a certain state of piety in the believers, while Da Vinci's painting was chosen because it was not very different from the first and seemed to be a comforting impression.
The test subjects spent half an hour in the MRI scanner and during this time they received in four consecutive parts 20 electroshocks while watching separately the picture with religious or general themes.
Catholics reported that looking at the Virgin Mary, they felt "safe " as if they had been" cared for " and" calmed down, filled with peace. "
They felt 12 percent less pain in view of the religious image than when Leonardo's work was before them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved using any highly impressive image even in atheists, just need to find the right photograph.
"We would have to find an image that they will perceive very positively, from the position of mother or father," said the psychologist.
Bishop Tom Wright of England welcomed the research results.
"The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it will also change our personality," Wright added.
After such excellent results, it is only a question of what effect it would have on regulating the pain of believers if they showed them a Madonna by Leonard or a painter of similar caliber.
Would the view of a quality Virgin Mary mean achieving even better results?
