An intelligent car mimics a bumblebee flight
What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not imitations of barriers occurring in the world of nature?
Bees, for example.
The initial strategic idea of a surprise project, presented at the Japanese CEATEC fair, inspired engineers from Nissan bumblebees. It was about how to build a new generation of systems to prevent collisions.
In cooperation with Tokyo University, Nissan has designed a biomimetic robotic control system type BR23C, a robotized miniaut that is equipped with bee properties, with the ultimate aim of helping to create a system that can eliminate any precipitation.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is actually very similar to our safety cover," explained Kazuhiro Doi, CEO of the brand for technological PR and research and development.
Folding eyes play an important role, allowing bees to see in all directions at an angle of vision of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the composite eye function, engineers reached for the idea of a laser ranger.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 metres in front of BR23C in the 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately transformed into an operation to prevent collision.
The obstacle is detected within a fraction of a second, then the robotized car starts mimicking the movements of the bee and turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent the collision immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this deflecting manoeuvre takes place in a completely instinctive way.
"If that were not the case, a robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshijuki Ando, Head of Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car Project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology meets the most vulnerable and inner layer of the safety packaging, within which the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
This process must not last longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed up, down or diagonally, it can only be two dimensional and only in a direction that can be turned.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees in avoiding them, only the possibility of rotating movement, acceleration and deceleration was applied in the case of a robotic car.
BR23C uses lithium polymer accumulators that are lighter and have higher energy density, which means they have longer lifespans than lithium ion variants.
According to Ando, instinctive, intelligent reactions are important, not the ability to process, the less data storage.
This mechanism must process and respond only to several incoming signals per second.
There is no need for him to keep them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so he keeps using only memory of a few kilobytes.
It does not need memory with giga- or megabajt capacity.
This is the first step towards developing an instant avoidance technology that, according to Nissan's estimate, could reach serially manufactured vehicles within ten years.
Another possibility of application may be to connect the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the motorist to the specified final destination after avoiding obstacles.
