The $700 billion economic rescue package, which is to be divided into several instalments and aimed at buying off low-quality bank loans, is already in writing.
Half the amount will be used in the first round.
After further negotiations, which ended on Saturday after midnight of US Eastern Time, Congress officials reached an agreement in a few days' debate on a $700 billion rescue package, Reuters reported.
"We have made significant progress," said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic President of the House of Representatives, according to which there is only an agreement to be drawn up.
Both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain also supported the compromise on the package.
Finance Minister Henry Paulson stated about the compromise: "The programme will work and will be effective, but further action needs to be taken. "
The written form of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets on Sunday at 8 p.m. Washington time (i.e. Monday at 2:00 a.m. Central European time), but no special increase in stock exchanges caused.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will vote first on the proposal for a legislative standard, which is in the name of the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilisation Act, and then it will be the Senate's turn.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night, and then they welcomed the news of the agreement to the White House.
"We are satisfied with the progress made at night, and we greatly appreciate both sides' efforts to stabilise our financial markets and protect our economy," said White House spokesperson Tony Fratto.
Indeed, the program differs from the Bush administration's original proposal, in which it was meant to be about spending the entire sum of $700 billion on the purchase of low-quality mortgage-backed securities.
Now it is possible to spend a maximum of half of 700 billion in the first, so that 250 billion will be used immediately after Congress decides on matters on Monday, and the Treasury will buy mortgage-backed securities that are classified as poor, the fate of the remaining $100 billion will depend on the president's decision.
The programme will be controlled by a special body, whose member will also be the chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank.
The spending of the second half of $700 billion will depend on another Congress decision.
The Ministry of Finance can apply combined tactics within the meaning of the law: it can simultaneously buy low-quality loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities or other "poisoned" loans.
The purchase can take place both within the auction and directly, communicated by the competent representatives of the Ministry.
The legal standard will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance programme in which the Ministry of Finance will guarantee them funds which constitute a cause for concern, for which the company will then pay the price corresponding to the amount of expected damage.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary resources to spend up to $700 billion to meet the urgent requirements of the US financial system, whether it is a large-scale purchase of bad funds, their insurance, or the prevention of systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the large money institutions.
"We will take the necessary steps to be prepared to implement the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the contrary, bank bosses who are in trouble and waiting to help the state can count on the government to cut their severance payments - simply called "gold parachute" in the overseas slang.
They will only be limited in certain cases, and these restrictions will depend on the method of assistance provided by the Ministry.
The limitation basically means that if the Ministry buys within the auction, a tax premium will be imposed on the golden parachutes if the fallen bank directors are not sent straight to retirement.
In the event of direct buy-in of low-quality loans, the government will aggressively intervene in order not to overestimate the money for management.
It must be added that the existing contracts on golden parachutes will not change, the restriction applies only to new contracts, which is to be another stimulus for participation in the programme.
"This is the first case in American history when the legal limitation on the remuneration of CEOs will be in force," commented Barney Frank, Democrat, Chairman of the Financial Services Committee of the House of Representatives.
In addition, the State will be entitled to a share in the banks participating in the programme, thereby reducing the risk of taxpayers, because once the economy and the rescued bank, together with it, can also make money from the transaction.
The draft plan contains that, in the next five years, the President must submit a proposal to Congress setting out how taxpayers can be recovered the expected losses from the financial sector.
Of course, there were also voices on both sides expressing doubts in relation to the plan.
"This is not what American citizens asked us to do, because this is not something that will protect taxpayers' dollars," said the Republican Congressman of California, Darrell Issa.
His democratic colleague from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, believes that exactly those responsible for the collapse of Wall Street urged the adoption of the provisions.
Industrial prices continued to rise
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 due to the previous month, by 12,9 percent compared to August 2007, the Central Statistical Office announced.
The export sales prices in the industry were 1,1% higher compared to July 2008, decreased year on year by 3.9 percent.
Production prices in the industry were 0.7 percent higher as a result of changes in domestic and export prices compared to the previous month, rising by 3.2 percent year on year.
Domestic sales prices in industry increased by at least 0.1 percent due to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing industry also slightly increased by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The biggest price increase took place in August 2008 in the leather and footwear industry (2.8 percent), mainly due to the month-on-month increase in prices in the bag and saddlery products industry by 4.6 percent, or to the production of footwear by 2.5 percent.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly increase in prices in the chemical and product industries (1.6%).
Prices decreased in the oil processing sector (1.4 per cent), production of electrical machinery and equipment (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
Prices in paper production and publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In other manufacturing industries, we measured price increases between 0.2 - 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas and water generation and distribution sectors, which have a significant weight in domestic sales of the industry, prices increased by 0.3 percent in August, mainly by the continued effect of the officially established increase in gas prices as of 1 July.
In the 12-month comparison of domestic sales in individual industries, prices increased most in the oil processing industry (32.4 percent).
In the manufacturing sector, 13.2% were observed, in the production of food products, beverages and tobacco products, which have a decisive weight, and in the 11 percent price increase.
Prices decreased in the textile and textile product industries (2,5 percent) and the production of electrical machinery and apparatus (0.3 percent).
In other manufacturing industries, the rate of price growth ranged between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing industry increased by 10.2 percent last year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water generation and distribution sector exceeded prices from the previous year by 18.7 percent.
From the point of view of the sector's focus, the highest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) in the production sectors of tangible assets was seen in domestic sales in August.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 percent, in the energy of processing and further processing sectors, prices did not change due to the previous month.
The biggest price increase due to the same month preceding the year was observed in August 2008 in the energy of processing and further processing industries (16.8 percent).
In the consumer goods industries, we measured a price increase of 6.8 percent, but for tangible assets, prices dropped by 1.4 percent.
The export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month and decreased by 3.9 percent in 12 months.
Our domestic currency has weakened by 1.7 percent in one month due to the euro, by 7.1 percent in relation to the dollar, by 7.5 percent in comparison to August 2007 and by 15.9 percent in relation to the dollar.
